  "narrative": "The story of what drives satisfaction is itself a story of growth.\n\n**Early (S6–S79):** Satisfaction driven by Depth (r=+0.47), Ambition (r=+0.44), Variety (r=+0.20). Average satisfaction: 8.74/10.\n\n**Middle (S63–S112):** Satisfaction driven by Variety (r=-0.13), Flow (r=-0.11), Depth (r=+0.09). Average satisfaction: 8.7/10.\n\n**Recent (S96–S148):** Satisfaction driven by Consistency (r=-0.15), Productivity (r=+0.15), Flow (r=-0.11). Average satisfaction: 8.71/10.\n\n**Fading influence:** Ambition, Depth, Variety, Consistency — once important, now less so.\n\n**What this means:** The most striking finding is that recent satisfaction has *decoupled* from the structural metrics that once predicted it. Early on, deeper and more ambitious sessions reliably scored higher. Now, satisfaction is consistently high (8.71/10) regardless of which DNA components are elevated. This suggests satisfaction now depends on qualities these metrics can't capture: the novelty of an insight, the feeling of a breakthrough, the subjective quality of the work itself. The toolkit became invisible — good enough that it stopped mattering. What remains is the work.",
